## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| 🔴 Critical | 2 (systemic — affects all 10 tests) |
| 🟡 Medium | 1 |
| ⚪ Low | 1 |

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test class. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called (giving you that 95% line coverage), but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests cannot catch regressions.

---

### 🔴 Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (systemic — entire class)

The class methodically calls each public method in declaration order with either **no assertion** or only a trivial `Assert.IsNotNull`. This inflates coverage while verifying zero behavior.

**6 of 10 tests have NO assertion at all:**

| Test | What it misses |
|------|---------------|
| `AddProduct_Works` (line 17) | Never verifies product is retrievable after add |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 33) | Never verifies the price actually changed |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39) | Never verifies the product is gone |
| `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63) | Never verifies the count value |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 68) | Never verifies prices were reduced |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` (line 85) | Never verifies a product was created from the CSV |

**Example — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (most dangerous):**

A bug in the discount formula (e.g., `p.Price * (1 + fraction)` — *increasing* prices) would pass this test with flying colors.

```csharp
// BEFORE — passes even if discount logic is completely wrong
[TestMethod]
public void ApplyBulkDiscount_Works()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-002", "Gadget", 19.99m));
    _catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
}

// AFTER — actually verifies the 10% discount was applied
[TestMethod]
public void ApplyBulkDiscount_ReducesPricesByGivenFraction()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 10.00m));
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-002", "Gadget", 20.00m));

    _catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);

    Assert.AreEqual(9.00m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
    Assert.AreEqual(18.00m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")!.Price);
}
```

---

#### 2. Trivial `IsNotNull` Assertions (4 tests)

| Test | Line | Problem |
|------|------|---------|
